    <problem>
        <title>P6</title>
        <p>The <alert>Sylvester sequence</alert> is the sequence of positive integers defined by <m>s_0=2</m> and <m>s_n=1+s_0s_1s_2\cdots s_{n-1}</m> for all <m>n\geq 1</m>.
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Prove by induction on <m>n</m> that for all <m>n\geq 1</m>, we have <m>s_n=s_{n-1}^2 - s_{n-1}+1</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Prove that if <m>p</m> is a prime number that divides <m>s_k</m> for some <m>k\geq 0</m>, then <m>p</m> does not divide <m>s_j</m> for any <m>j\gt k</m>.
                        Explain why this implies that there are infinitely many prime numbers.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Explain in a few sentences how the Sylvester sequence is related to Euclid's proof of the infinitude of primes.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </problem>

    <problem>
        <title>P7</title>
        <p>We will show in this problem how the fundamental theorem of arithmetic can be used to prove that there are infinitely many primes.
            Recall that <m>\pi(N)</m> is the number of primes less than or equal to <m>N</m>.
            This problem will lead you through the steps of a proof due to Paul Erd≈ës.
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Prove that every integer <m>n</m> can be expressed as <m>n=a^2b</m>, where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are positive integers and <m>b</m> is square-free (meaning that no prime number divides <m>b</m> more than once).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Prove that there are at most <m>2^{\pi(N)}</m> square-free integers less than or equal to <m>N</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Prove that there are at most <m>\sqrt{N}</m> integers less than or equal to <m>N</m> that are of the form <m>a^2</m> for some positive integer <m>a</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Use the previous parts to prove that <m>N\leq 2^{\pi(N)}\sqrt{N}</m> for all positive integers <m>N</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Show that the inequality in the previous part implies that <m>\pi(n)\geq \frac{\log(n)}{\log(4)}</m> for all <m>n\geq 1</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Explain why this proves that there are infinitely many prime numbers.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </problem>

    <problem>
        <title>P8</title>
        <p>The following problem is an open problem in mathematics, meaning that it is a problem that has not been solved by anyone.
            The <alert>Euclid-Mullin sequence</alert> is the sequence of prime numbers that starts with <m>2</m> and continues by taking the smallest prime number produced by a Euclid step, as defined in <xref ref="infinitudeofprimes"/>.
            Thus, the Euclid-Mullin sequence starts with <me>2,3,7,43,13,53,5,6221671,38709183810571, 139, \ldots \, .</me>
            If you are interested, you can read about this sequence at <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%E2%80%93Mullin_sequence"/>.
        </p>
          <p>The open problem is: Does every prime number appear in the Euclid-Mullin sequence?
            For example, no one knows whether or not the prime <m>41</m> is produced by this process.
        </p>
        <p>
            Make as much progress as you can on this open problem; I don't expect you to find a solution, but you should spend 2-3 hours thinking about this!
            Your goal is to do something more than check examples; the examples should lead you to make some interesting observations about the problem, to understand it a bit better.
            Why do you think it might be true?  
            Why might it be false?
            Are there any properties of binomial coefficients that support your comments?
            Are there any positive integers for which this is obviously true?
            You can do this using only pencil and paper, or using mostly computational experiments, or you can use a mix of these.
            However, you need to provide a narrative in sentences/paragraphs explaining your thinking and the results of your investigations.
            (Seriously, write down everything you're thinking and every idea you try, even if it doesn't go anywhere.)
        </p>
    </problem>

